image.altText: The interior of the Singapore Airlines plane

props.synopsis: A 73-year-old British man has died and dozens are injured after a Singapore Airlines flight from London struck "severe turbulence" and was forced to make an emergency landing in Bangkok.

title.children: British man likely died of heart attack, officials say, after London-Singapore flight hit severe turbulence

image.altText: A composite image of Meng Wong standing outside of Suncorp bank, and a bank invoice for 80 thousand dollars.

props.synopsis: False documentation might be one of the oldest scams in the book but scammers are now able to fake being a company more easily — and Australians are falling for it.

title.children: Meng lost $80,000 after scammers impersonated his email. Two banks said there was nothing they could do

image.altText: A large aeroplane sits with its back door open on the tarmac as people with bags walk toward it

props.synopsis: More than 100 Australians and other tourists stranded for up to a week in the violence in New Caledonia have been repatriated.

title.children: First repatriation flights from riot-stricken New Caledonia arrive in Australia

image.altText: A couple smiles as they take a selfie.

props.synopsis: The federal regulator has taken action against two more doctors as part of an investigation into a clinic following the death of a woman soon after a surgical abortion at a health clinic in Melbourne's south-east.

title.children: Two more doctors suspended following investigation into Melbourne woman's death after abortion

image.altText: William Tyrrell in red shirt, sitting in chair with drink

props.synopsis: Detectives investigating the disappearance of toddler William Tyrrell have asked the prosecutors looking into the toddler's foster mother to suspend their inquiry until a coronial inquest resumes at the end of this year.

title.children: Police ask prosecutors to suspend inquiry into William Tyrrell's former foster mother

image.altText: Telstra Shop signage outside Brisbane CBD store

props.synopsis: Telstra reveals plans to sack up to 2,800 workers as part of its latest cost-cutting measures, with most of these job losses to occur by the end of this year.

title.children: Telstra's 'massive change' has 'blindsided' workers, but will it pay off for customers and shareholders?

image.altText: A composite image of an older man and an older woman smiling.

props.synopsis: The jury in Greg Lynn's murder trial hears slain camper Russell Hill hid his affair with childhood sweetheart Carol Clay by telling others they were first cousins.

title.children: Wife of slain Victorian camper did not know husband was still seeing secret lover when he disappeared, murder trial hears

image.altText: Rows of dead birds including skuas and penguins.

props.synopsis: A deadly strain of avian influenza has breached the world's most remote continent. Scientists say it's only a matter of time before it reaches Australia.

title.children: On the planet's most remote continent, a deadly virus is leaving a 'trail of destruction' that has scientists on edge

image.altText: Albanese wearing a white hard hat and yellow vest flanked by two others in the same outfit

props.synopsis: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton accuses Prime Minister Anthony Albanese of weakness for failing to criticise the International Criminal Court's prosecutor.

title.children: Dutton condemns Albanese for refusing to condemn Netanyahu arrest warrant request

image.altText: Two soldiers holding a man with a mask with Benjamin Netanyahu's face on it.

props.synopsis: The International Criminal Court prosecutor's office has requested arrest warrants for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his defence chief, and also for three Hamas leaders for alleged war crimes and crimes against humanity. So what happens next?

title.children: Why is the ICC seeking warrants for Israeli and Hamas leaders, hasn't this already happened and who is involved? What you need to know

image.altText: Shot of steel gate with sign saying "Commonwealth of Australia"

props.synopsis: A former immigration detainee, released after the High Court ruled indefinite detention was unlawful, receives a suspended sentence for breaching his curfew and letting his GPS tracker's battery run out.

title.children: Ex-immigration detainee released back into community after failing to keep ankle monitor battery charged

image.altText: Man in black polo shirt in front of highway with blurred clouds behind

props.synopsis: For the first time since Richard Roe’s car was found abandoned on the side of the Stuart Highway in 2016, his family has a chance to hear about his possible fate, as an inquest into his disappearance begins.

title.children: 'Is Richard buried at your property?': Explosive evidence heard in cold case missing man inquest

image.altText: An iPhone shows various apps against a black background.

props.synopsis: Many Australian consumers are unaware of the extent of personal data being collected about them on a day-to-day basis, says a new report.

title.children: It would take almost 46 hours to read every privacy policy you agree to in a month. Here's why that's concerning

image.altText: Tarryn Thomas playing for the Kangaroos

props.synopsis: The AFL responds as former North Melbourne star Tarryn Thomas faces charges over the alleged harassment of a former partner.

title.children: AFL issues statement as Tarryn Thomas faces charges over alleged harassment of former partner

image.altText: A grand looking building is surrounded by palm trees.

props.synopsis: New laws that allow the NT police commissioner to declare snap curfews in response to social unrest have passed through parliament, despite concerns from some that they amount to government overreach.

title.children: Controversial curfew laws have passed NT Parliament. Here's what you need to know

image.altText: Bill Shorten At National Press Club

props.synopsis: As a parliamentary hearing kicks off into draft legislation paving the way for changes to the NDIS, a governmental stoush has re-emerged. Here's what's going on.

title.children: 'Get this right quickly': The governmental stoush over the NDIS explained

image.altText: A blue ANZ Bank sign is seen at a bank branch in Martin Place, Sydney.

props.synopsis: The bank says it is investigating a technology issue relating to a third party vendor.

title.children: ANZ online banking and app services beginning to 'come back online' after major outage, bank says

image.altText: A split image shows a computer with red logo taken from a still from the film Her, and a woman with green mesh over her face

props.synopsis: This week in tech news, OpenAI drops a new chatbot voice bearing a striking resemblance to Scarlett Johansson's, federal parliament discusses laws on political deepfakes, and the internet continues to be a terrifying place to be a teenager.

title.children: Deepfakes in an Australian election campaign would be legally fine, and OpenAI benches its flirty new chatbot voice

image.altText: A large ship with containers on top and crushed metal at the front, with a small tugboat next to it

props.synopsis: The recovery from the deadly Baltimore bridge collapse reached a significant milestone as tugboats escorted the ill-fated container ship Dali back to port.

title.children: Ship that slammed into the Baltimore bridge moved two months later

image.altText: A man wearing a Woolworths polo shirt with the name tag 'Brad' stands in a supermarket.

props.synopsis: Woolworths boss Brad Banducci has defended the amount of food the supermarket giant rejects with a top executive saying no one wants a banana that is "too big", a South Australian parliamentary inquiry has heard.

title.children: Woolworths CEO says supermarket contributes 'very little' to food waste

image.altText: A woman in yellow jumper holding shopping bag faces a supermarket shelf full of colourful wrapped foods.

props.synopsis: Queensland Treasurer Cameron Dick says cost-of-living relief is one of the reasons the state is forecast to fall billions of dollars into deficit. Economists say there could be three reasons for it.

title.children: Queensland is forecast to record a budget deficit of $3bn. Economists explain why

image.altText: Dr Peter Renshaw sits in front of a microphone.

props.synopsis: Last week it was announced six deaths at a major Tasmanian hospital would be investigated over allegations of falsifying death certificates — authorities have now widened the probe to include another 63 deaths.

title.children: Dozens more cases to be investigated over alleged falsifying of death certificates at major Tasmanian hospital

image.altText: design render for memorial

props.synopsis: An initial design for the memorial for victims of child sexual abuse, which will be built on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin in Canberra, had to be scrapped due to "complex construction challenges". It's now expected to be built in 2026.

title.children: This memorial was to be made of glass, but it's since been found it poses 'challenges' and should be scrapped

image.altText: The back profile of a woman looking at her shadow

props.synopsis: A Tasmanian court has heard audio from triple-0 calls, documenting the moment an ex-butcher broke into his home and attacked his wife with a knife, before neighbours intervened after hearing the victim's screams.

title.children: 'You know how this ends': Man's knife attack on wife heard in triple-0 calls

image.altText: A woman with long blonde hair sits on a pink couch and looks into the distance.

props.synopsis: When Jo O'Brien lost $500,000 to a scammer, she set out to track him down, eventually finding the man she believed was responsible. She sent him a text.

title.children: Jo was scammed out of $500,000. She threatened to 'ruin' lives to get her life savings back

image.altText: A composite image of women, one in a hijab crying and two with drinks in their hand.

props.synopsis: While government loyalists pack mosques and squares to pray for President Ebrahim Raisi, most shops remain open and the authorities make little effort to interrupt ordinary life.

title.children: While some women mourn the death of Iran's president, others hurt by the regime are celebrating

image.altText: Nina taking a selfie with her son Jerome, both are smiling.

props.synopsis: Children are gathering large followings and earning thousands of dollars through social media influencing — but some warn it comes with a dark side.

title.children: Jerome is a 4yo model who makes thousands of dollars. But his social media fame has a dark side

image.altText: Table strewn with old photos, cards, books, jewellery, a tea cup, small clock, carved jewellery box and pop culture ornament

props.synopsis: This museum curator explains why we should bring our childhood toys, old band T-shirts and family heirlooms out of hiding and honour them for the memories they contain.

title.children: How to honour your boxes of sentimental 'stuff' and know when to let them go

image.altText: Linda Reynolds perth court

props.synopsis: Senator Linda Reynolds' defamation action against her former staffer Brittany Higgins appears destined for trial as mediation talks in Perth break down again.

title.children: Defamation trial between Linda Reynolds and Brittany Higgins appears likely as mediation collapses

image.altText: Two men answer questions during a press conference.

props.synopsis: Spurs manager Ange Postecoglou says his team's clash with Newcastle United at the MCG on Wednesday will not overshadow the A-League Men's grand final on Saturday.

title.children: Ange Postecoglou 'bewildered' over talk that Tottenham visit will overshadow A-League Men grand final

image.altText: people walking past large sandstone arches in uq st lucia's great court

props.synopsis: Wiley's Hindawi scandal offers a window into a thriving black market of fake science, corrupted research and bogus authorship. It also illuminates a much broader crisis of trust confronting universities and scientific institutions worldwide.

title.children: The Wiley scandal illuminates a much bigger crisis of trust confronting universities around the world

image.altText: Anya Taylor-Joy, Michelle Yeoh, Selene Gomez and Rawdah Mohamed

props.synopsis: Unlike the Oscars or Golden Globes where most of the action happens in one night, the Cannes Film Festival is a marathon of events — and a buffet of fashion.

title.children: More red carpet looks from the fashionable fortnight of Cannes

image.altText: A man standing in front of a huge home

props.synopsis: There is room for eight bedrooms, 10 bathrooms, 14 car spaces, a ballroom, two wine cellars, two lifts and a dining table that seats 22 people.

title.children: GJ Gardner Homes founder starts work on $12m mansion in Noosa hinterland, modelled on a French chateau
